                <!-- Section 3: The 16 KB Solve -->
                <section id="the-16kb-fix" class="bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-slate-100 scroll-mt-6">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
                        <span class="text-primary-600">03.</span> The 16 KB Page Support Solve
                    </h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                        Starting with Android 15, the OS began introducing support for larger **16 KB memory page sizes** alongside traditional 4 KB page sizes. To run correctly on a 16 KB device, all native shared library files (<code class="bg-slate-100 text-rose-600 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded font-mono text-sm">.so</code>) packaged inside the APK must be aligned on a **16 KB segment boundary**.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="bg-rose-50 border-l-4 border-rose-500 p-4 rounded-r-xl mb-6">
                        <p class="text-sm text-rose-800 font-semibold mb-1">The Problem we Analyzed:</p>
                        <p class="text-xs text-rose-700 leading-relaxed">
                            The bundled ML Kit OCR/Text-Recognition library (<code class="bg-rose-100/60 text-rose-800 px-1 rounded font-mono">com.google.mlkit:text-recognition:16.0.0</code>) contained a compiled native library called <code class="bg-rose-100/60 text-rose-800 px-1 rounded font-mono">libmlkit_google_ocr_pipeline.so</code> with **4 KB LOAD section alignment**. Because of this, the APK analyzer generated the warning: <strong>"Does not support 16 KB devices"</strong>, which causes crashes or failures when running on Android 15 / 16 platforms with 16 KB hardware enabled.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="bg-success-50 border-l-4 border-success-500 p-4 rounded-r-xl mb-6">
                        <p class="text-sm text-success-800 font-semibold mb-1">Our Optimal Solution:</p>
                        <p class="text-xs text-success-700 leading-relaxed">
                            We switched the dependency definition from the heavy, bundled standalone client to the **thin, dynamic Google Play Services Client** for ML Kit Text Recognition:
                        </p>
                        <div class="mt-2 text-xs text-slate-800 font-mono bg-slate-900 text-slate-200 p-3 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto">
<span class="text-emerald-400"># BEFORE: Standalone client with 4 KB unaligned binary</span>
mlkitTextRecognition = "16.0.1"
mlkit-text-recognition = { group = "com.google.mlkit", name = "text-recognition", version.ref = "mlkitTextRecognition" }

<span class="text-emerald-400"># AFTER: Thin client loading from Play Services</span>
mlkitTextRecognition = "19.0.1"
mlkit-text-recognition = { group = "com.google.android.gms", name = "play-services-mlkit-text-recognition", version.ref = "mlkitTextRecognition" }
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- Section 4: Play Services Advantage -->
                <section id="why-playservices" class="bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-slate-100 scroll-mt-6">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
                        <span class="text-primary-600">04.</span> Why Using Google Play Services is Superior
                    </h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                        Transitioning to <code class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-700 px-1 py-0.5 rounded font-mono">play-services-mlkit-text-recognition</code> has three key architectural advantages:
                    </p>

                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-primary-100 text-primary-700 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-xs mt-1">1</span>
                            <div>
                                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-800 text-base">Dramatic APK Size Reduction</h4>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                                    The bundled client forces the compiler to package heavy <code class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-700 px-1 rounded font-mono">.so</code> libraries and pre-trained neural networks directly inside the final <code class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-700 px-1 rounded font-mono">.apk</code> file, ballooning the size by **10-15 MB**. Play Services dynamically provisions the library, resulting in a much faster, smaller download.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-primary-100 text-primary-700 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-xs mt-1">2</span>
                            <div>
                                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-800 text-base">Zero Code Modification Needed</h4>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                                    Because both libraries share identical package pathways (<code class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-700 px-1 rounded font-mono">com.google.mlkit.vision.text.*</code>), your Kotlin screens (<code class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-700 px-1 rounded font-mono">ScannerScreen.kt</code>, <code class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-700 px-1 rounded font-mono">PdfToPptScreen.kt</code>, etc.) do not require code changes. The migration is perfectly transparent to compile-time checkers.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                            <span class="flex-shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-primary-100 text-primary-700 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-xs mt-1">3</span>
                            <div>
                                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-800 text-base">Auto-Download Model Configuration</h4>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                                    By placing the download declaration directly in the app’s manifest, Google Play services manages model downloads automatically when users install the application from the Play Store:
                                </p>
                                <div class="mt-2 text-xs text-slate-800 font-mono bg-slate-900 text-slate-200 p-3 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto">
&lt;meta-data
    android:name="com.google.mlkit.vision.DEPENDENCIES"
    android:value="ocr" /&gt;
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

